ce:section.ce:para:
To investigate the influence of various anions and ROS on the detection of MCDs with HOCl, the analysis was conducted in the presence of 15 μM of anions and HOCl. The fluorescence intensity of the MCDs was investigated in mixtures containing different anions, and the results indicated that the intensity was similar to that of HOCl alone (Fig. 3
                     ). These findings suggest that other ROS had negligible effects on the detection of MCDs when combined with HOCl [53]. The absorbance and fluorescence quenching of MCDs in the presence of HOCl ions were measured between 0 and 15 μM, as demonstrated in Fig. 4
                     a and b. The fluorescence intensity at 441 nm reached its maximum at 15 μM of HOCl, with a remarkable linear correlation of R2 = 0.9907, as revealed in Figure S5 [54]. The MCDs exhibited highly sensitive detection of HOCl in DI-water, with a detection limit of 3.38 nM, making the probe suitable for identifying the basal HOCl level in cells. Furthermore, the quantum yield (0.594) of the product generated from the reaction between MCDs and HOCl was found to be 0.052, exhibiting a fluorescence enhancement of approximately 11.423 times less than that of MCDs. This approach exhibits a notably high level of precision compared to alternative methods (as shown in Table 1
                     ).
